For scraping rosters from 300+ college athletics sites at scale, here are the options ranked by ease and reliability:

## Recommended Approach: Headless Browser with DOM Parsing

**Best option**: Use **Playwright** or **Puppeteer** with DOM parsing

```typescript
// Example with Playwright
import { chromium } from 'playwright';

async function scrapeRoster(url: string) {
  const browser = await chromium.launch();
  const page = await browser.newPage();

  await page.goto(url);
  await page.waitForSelector('[class*="roster"]'); // Wait for roster to load

  // Extract roster data from DOM
  const players = await page.$$eval('.player-item', elements => 
    elements.map(el => ({
      name: el.querySelector('.player-name')?.textContent?.trim(),
      position: el.querySelector('.position')?.textContent?.trim(),
      number: el.querySelector('.jersey-number')?.textContent?.trim(),
      year: el.querySelector('.academic-year')?.textContent?.trim(),
      // ... etc
    }))
  );

  await browser.close();
  return players;
}
```

### Why This is Best:

1. **Handles SSR/CSR/Hybrid** - Works regardless of how sites render (server-side, client-side, or hybrid)
2. **JavaScript Execution** - Executes all JS, so data loads naturally
3. **Consistent Experience** - Gets the same data a user would see
4. **Framework Agnostic** - Doesn't matter if it's Nuxt, Next.js, React, Vue, or plain HTML

## Alternative Approaches (Less Reliable at Scale):

### 2. Static HTML Parsing (Cheerio/Beautiful Soup)
- **Pros**: Fast, lightweight
- **Cons**: Only works for SSR sites; fails if data loads via JS
- **Use if**: You confirm all 300 sites are purely SSR

### 3. Extracting Embedded State
```typescript
// Extract from __NUXT__ or __NEXT_DATA__
const stateScript = await page.$eval('script', el => {
  if (el.textContent.includes('__NUXT__')) {
    return JSON.parse(el.textContent.match(/__NUXT__\s*=\s*({.+})/)[1]);
  }
});
```
- **Cons**: Every framework embeds differently; fragile across sites

## Production Architecture for 300+ Sites:

```typescript
// Scalable scraping system
import { Queue } from 'bullmq';
import { chromium } from 'playwright';

interface ScrapeJob {
  schoolName: string;
  rosterUrl: string;
  sport: string;
}

class RosterScraper {
  private browser;

  async init() {
    this.browser = await chromium.launch({ headless: true });
  }

  async scrapeWithRetry(url: string, maxRetries = 3) {
    for (let i = 0; i < maxRetries; i++) {
      try {
        const page = await this.browser.newPage();

        // Set timeout and user agent
        await page.setUserAgent('Mozilla/5.0...');

        // Go to page
        await page.goto(url, { waitUntil: 'networkidle', timeout: 30000 });

        // Generic selectors that work across multiple platforms
        const selectors = [
          '.roster-player',
          '[data-test="player"]',
          'tr[class*="player"]',
          '.athlete-item'
        ];

        // Try each selector
        for (const selector of selectors) {
          const count = await page.locator(selector).count();
          if (count > 0) {
            const data = await this.extractData(page, selector);
            await page.close();
            return data;
          }
        }

        throw new Error('No roster data found');

      } catch (err) {
        if (i === maxRetries - 1) throw err;
        await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 2000 * (i + 1))); // Exponential backoff
      }
    }
  }

  async extractData(page, selector) {
    return await page.$$eval(selector, elements => 
      elements.map(el => ({
        name: el.querySelector('[class*="name"]')?.textContent?.trim(),
        position: el.querySelector('[class*="position"]')?.textContent?.trim(),
        number: el.querySelector('[class*="number"], [class*="jersey"]')?.textContent?.trim(),
        year: el.querySelector('[class*="year"], [class*="class"]')?.textContent?.trim(),
        height: el.querySelector('[class*="height"]')?.textContent?.trim(),
        hometown: el.querySelector('[class*="hometown"], [class*="home-town"]')?.textContent?.trim(),
      }))
    );
  }
}

// Use a queue for managing 300 sites
const queue = new Queue('roster-scraping');

// Add jobs
const schools = [...]; // Your 300 sites
schools.forEach(school => {
  queue.add('scrape-roster', {
    schoolName: school.name,
    rosterUrl: school.rosterUrl,
    sport: school.sport
  });
});

// Process with concurrency control
const worker = new Worker('roster-scraping', async (job) => {
  const scraper = new RosterScraper();
  await scraper.init();
  const data = await scraper.scrapeWithRetry(job.data.rosterUrl);
  // Save to database
  return data;
}, { concurrency: 5 }); // Run 5 at a time to avoid rate limits
```

## Key Considerations for Scale:

1. **Rate Limiting**: Don't hammer servers; use delays between requests
2. **Browser Pooling**: Reuse browser instances to save resources
3. **Proxy Rotation**: If scraping at high volume, rotate IPs
4. **Error Handling**: Many sites will be down/changed; handle gracefully
5. **Caching**: Store scraped data with timestamps; don't re-scrape unnecessarily
6. **Monitoring**: Track success rates per site/platform

## Platform Detection:

Many college sites use the same platforms. Detect and optimize:

```typescript
const platforms = {
  'SIDEARM': ['gofrogs.com', 'goblueraiders.com'], // Most common
  'PrestoSports': [...],
  'Playfly': [...],
  'Custom': [...]
};

// Build platform-specific scrapers
```

**Bottom Line**: Use Playwright with DOM parsing for the most reliable, scalable solution. It's more resource-intensive than static parsing but will work across all rendering strategies.

